cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.HC 

This paper is likely to belong to the following arXiv CS sub-categories: 

1. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks): The paper studies the dynamics of message production in a many-to-many social communication activity on a popular technology-news website. It analyzes the statistics of these activities and identifies daily and weekly oscillatory cycles. This is a clear indication that the paper belongs to the cs.SI sub-category. 

2. cs.CY (Computers and Society): The paper discusses the behavior of a large online communication space and how it can be described using a few parameters. It also highlights the surprising finding that only a few parameters can predict social many-to-many information exchange in this kind of popular public spaces. This makes it likely that the paper belongs to the cs.CY sub-category. 

3. cs.SD (Software Engineering): The paper does not focus on software engineering, but it does analyze the behavior of a large online communication space, which involves the use of software. This makes it possible that the paper belongs to the cs.SD sub-category. 

4. cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks): The paper studies the dynamics of message production in a many-to-many social communication activity on a popular technology-news website. This is a clear indication that the paper belongs to the cs.SOC sub-category.
